        <p data-sal-repeat="data-sal-repeat" data-sal="slide-right" data-sal-duration="1000" data-sal-easing="ease-out-back">Students helping students is a great way to solve relatable problems. Through texting other students over the course of three meetings between mid-September and election day, we'll increase voter turnout. Since each of these meetings is only 1-2 hours long, our workload is kept light (for both the people sending and receiving info). Using this strategy, it's suddenly not so intimidating to help students figure out if they're registered, how to mail in their ballot, whether to vote in or out of state, and remembering to turnout on election day.</p>
        <p data-sal-repeat="data-sal-repeat" data-sal="slide-right" data-sal-duration="1000" data-sal-easing="ease-out-back">The two roles are pretty similar in the end, but organizers put in a little extra time recruiting other students and considering how best to further develop our work.</p>
