<div class="inner-section" id="greater-vision">
    <h2 class="title" data-sal-repeat="data-sal-repeat" data-sal="zoom-out" data-sal-duration="1000" data-sal-easing="ease-out-back">The Greater Vision</h2>
    <p data-sal-repeat="data-sal-repeat" data-sal="slide-right" data-sal-duration="1000" data-sal-easing="ease-out-back">Institutionalize voting.</p>

    <p data-sal-repeat="data-sal-repeat" data-sal="slide-right" data-sal-duration="1000" data-sal-easing="ease-out-back">Our Student Government Association already signed off on the
        <a class="link" href="https://www.evcnational.org/blogpost/jumpstarting-our-campus-presence-with-time-off-to-vote" target="_blank">Time Off To Vote letter</a>, but now we should aim for improvements specific to our campus.</p>

    <p data-sal-repeat="data-sal-repeat" data-sal="slide-right" data-sal-duration="1000" data-sal-easing="ease-out-back">UVM has a handful of voting resources, but they're off the beaten path. We could move these resources into the mainstream a few ways. In the physical sense, that might look like registering voters during orientation days, while in the digital sense, it could look like a featuring of resources in the myUVM portal. Stanford has already
        <a class="link" target="_blank" href="https://www.stanforddaily.com/2020/02/06/new-enrollment-hold-encourages-students-to-register-to-vote/">rolled out a system</a>
        where registering to vote is a class-registration hold until you explicitly acknowledge you've considered registering.</p>

    <p data-sal-repeat="data-sal-repeat" data-sal="slide-right" data-sal-duration="1000" data-sal-easing="ease-out-back">It's easy to imagine how UVM supporting student voters as a core value would increase turnout.</p>
